         <div type="entry">
                <head>Nuḥ the Lebanese</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Nuh-the-Lebanese</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/413</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">404</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="313-314"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/277</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Author, maph. (1489/90–1493), and <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr>
                        (1493–1509).<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(1451–1509) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Author, maph. (1489/90–1493), and <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> (1493–1509). Born into a Maronite
                        family, he became <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr> and studied at <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Musa-al-Habashi-Dayr-Mar">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/228">Dayr Mār
                            Mūsā al-Ḥabashī</placeName>
                        </ref> near <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Hims">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/215">Ḥimṣ</placeName>
                        </ref>. According to the
                        continuator of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Bar-Ebroyo-Grigorios">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/239">Bar ʿEbroyo</persName>
                        </ref>’s Ecclesiastical History
                        he had an excellent knowledge of both Syriac and Arabic. He was ordained <abbr>bp.</abbr>
                        of Ḥimṣ with the name Qurillos. He is the author of a number of <hi rend="italic">memre</hi> in the dodecasyllabic meter on several subjects
                        (ascetical, theological, and philosophical; injustice committed by Huns and
                        Kurds; an elegy on his teacher Tumo) (published by <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Dolabani-Philoxenos-Yuhanon">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/454">Yuḥanon
                            Dolabani</persName>
                        </ref> [Mardin, 1956]). As <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> he had to intervene in the
                        conflict which opposed <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Masud-of-Tur-Abdin">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/279">Masʿūd of Ṭur
                            ʿAbdin</persName>
                        </ref> and some senior bishops of the region.</p>
                </div>
